WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.280
Hi everyone, it seems to be working.

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:17.959
So I'm here today to talk about some of the extension mechanisms that have been built

00:00:17.959 --> 00:00:24.000
into ggplot2 and maybe kind of demystify them a bit in the process because I don't think

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.160
there are too many who knows about them or at least knows how to do them.

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:33.080
So I guess most of you use ggplot2 or have used it, but just a quick show of hands, who

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:37.160
has looked into extending ggplot2?

00:00:37.160 --> 00:00:38.160
That's pretty nice.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:39.520
That's more than I expected.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:46.959
So 20 minutes is precious little to talk about the extension system because it's big and

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:50.119
it's sprawling and it's somewhat complicated.

00:00:50.119 --> 00:00:55.200
So I'm just going to give you a quick overview about it and then in the end I'm going to

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:58.360
kind of point you in the direction of where to learn more.

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:02.500
And I'll of course be here and you can talk to me all you want after the fact.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:09.400
So ggplot2 has been gradually expanding its extension mechanism from the point where it

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:13.040
gets introduced in ggplot2 version 2.

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:17.720
Before that it was kind of a here be dragons situation if you wanted to extend ggplot2,

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:23.559
but at that point we, or Hadley and Winston at that time, decided to kind of formalize

00:01:23.559 --> 00:01:25.160
all of this.

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:30.760
Part of the reason was that people kept asking for new things in ggplot2 and ggplot2 is already

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:35.440
pretty big, as has been discussed before, and it's simply not feasible for us to include

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:40.320
all possible visualization possibilities into ggplot2 itself.

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.199
It's much better to kind of spread it out on multiple maintainers, multiple specific

00:01:44.199 --> 00:01:45.360
packages and so on.

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:52.639
So the better extension system that we get, the more is simply possible for you guys.

00:01:52.639 --> 00:01:55.199
There are a bunch of extensions point at this moment.

00:01:55.199 --> 00:01:58.720
There's themes and there's scales and there's, yeah, you can see them all up there.

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:04.360
They are not arranged kind of randomly because they are not equal.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:10.000
There are some that are dead simple to write and there are some that are, well, frightening.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.779
And that's just how it is because some things in visualization is kind of frightening.

00:02:15.779 --> 00:02:20.320
Not in the sense that you will explode or whatever, but it's just some things are just

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:23.199
extremely difficult to do.

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:26.600
And facets is absolutely one of the worst things to do.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:29.399
So I'm not going to dive into that at this moment.

00:02:29.399 --> 00:02:33.000
Further, there are some other stuff.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.759
There are a guide system that is being overhauled at this moment, and there is also a theme

00:02:37.759 --> 00:02:38.759
element.

00:02:38.759 --> 00:02:45.000
So Klaus showed the element markdown theme element, and it should work now, but we're

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.479
still in kind of a phase where we are figuring out precisely how we want to approach this.

00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:54.600
So while you may be able to do it right now, and there are guide extensions, but they are

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:57.380
not kind of officially supported at the moment.

00:02:57.380 --> 00:03:02.759
So just hold your horses for a bit with that if you can, and otherwise just be prepared

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:05.440
for breaking code at some point.

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:08.520
There is also a danger zone to look out for.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:12.339
So these are actually possible extension points.

00:03:12.339 --> 00:03:16.860
You can define what should happen when you plus something to your ggplot for a new kind

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:18.440
of object.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:23.500
It is possible to define how the rendering should happen, but this is definitely one

00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:25.839
of those hereby dragon things.

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:27.779
You may want to do this.

00:03:27.779 --> 00:03:31.259
This is patchwork, gganimate area.

00:03:31.259 --> 00:03:35.300
Those could not work without these kind of extension points, but it is also one of these

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:40.660
things that you can really blow up your package, and when we change something in ggplot2, you

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:43.619
may have to rewrite a considerable amount of code.

00:03:43.619 --> 00:03:49.220
So if you don't need it, don't go there.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:55.539
So just to start off real quickly with maybe the easiest way to extend ggplot2 is to make

00:03:55.539 --> 00:04:00.059
a new theme, and new themes are really, really relevant.

00:04:00.059 --> 00:04:04.899
You can define your theme for your corporation or whatever, and they are really easy because

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:08.220
it is really just ggplot2 code.

00:04:08.220 --> 00:04:12.899
You are used to defining themes when you are doing your plots, and you can simply wrap

00:04:12.899 --> 00:04:14.419
that in a function.

00:04:14.419 --> 00:04:18.100
Instead of using the plus mark, you use this replace operator, but other than that, this

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:23.299
is simply ggplot2 code as you expect it to look like, and you can, of course, do things

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:27.220
that are much more interesting than putting a red background on your plot, so you can

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:29.940
just go crazy there.

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:34.899
But this is also like the extent of normal code that you will see in extensions.

00:04:34.899 --> 00:04:39.859
There's a reason why I'm here, and I'm talking to you about this, because all the other things

00:04:39.859 --> 00:04:46.420
are based on this entity called ggproto, which is, yay, another object-oriented system in

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:57.899
R. And ggproto is kind of this weird object-oriented system that is only relevant for ggplot2 extensions.

00:04:57.899 --> 00:05:01.859
It is tailor-made for ggplot2.

00:05:01.859 --> 00:05:07.260
The reason why it's something new is that it needed to be a reference-based object-oriented

00:05:07.260 --> 00:05:14.459
system, and the current or at that time current object-oriented systems didn't allow subclassing

00:05:14.459 --> 00:05:15.980
objects between packages.

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:20.820
So if you want to make extensions, of course, you need to be able to subclass between ggplot2

00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:21.820
and into your own package.

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:25.619
So Winston sat down and made something new.

00:05:25.619 --> 00:05:29.140
The good thing about this, in some sense, is that ggproto is completely hidden from

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:30.140
the user.

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:33.619
So if this is the first time you hear about ggproto, fear not.

00:05:33.619 --> 00:05:36.420
This is how it should be.

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:38.339
But on the other hand, it's also weird.

00:05:38.339 --> 00:05:44.140
So when you want to transition into writing extensions, you come into this completely

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:47.540
new territory that you've never seen before.

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:52.299
So code may look foreign to you, because it's a new system and some new semantics.

00:05:52.299 --> 00:05:56.899
But don't worry, because it's not really as bad as it should appear.

00:05:56.899 --> 00:06:03.940
So basically ggproto is this scaffolding thing that holds all of ggplot together.

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:09.019
And it is used to orchestrate all the rendering and all the mechanics of how ggplot uses your

00:06:09.019 --> 00:06:13.420
data and transforms it into a plot.

00:06:13.420 --> 00:06:17.980
So when you think about how ggproto at least should be used when you're writing extensions

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:24.339
to ggplot2 and how ggplot2 uses it itself, is that you have to think about ggproto classes

00:06:24.339 --> 00:06:26.779
as somewhat of factories.

00:06:27.660 --> 00:06:35.820
These are classes that are stateless in the sense that you have an object, and it receives

00:06:35.820 --> 00:06:39.420
some data, and it does something to the data, and it spits out the data again.

00:06:39.420 --> 00:06:42.619
It doesn't keep track of what it has been doing in that sense.

00:06:42.619 --> 00:06:47.100
So this is really important, because when you plot a second time, you don't want it

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:48.100
to change.

00:06:48.100 --> 00:06:51.579
You want it to behave as it should be every time you plot it.

00:06:51.579 --> 00:06:56.019
So all of these ggproto objects are more or less stateless.

00:06:56.260 --> 00:06:58.299
There are a few that you shouldn't touch that are not stateless.

00:06:58.299 --> 00:07:03.540
But for every kind of idea of extensions, you should think of these as kind of factories.

00:07:03.540 --> 00:07:10.940
You have this assembly line, and each method is kind of this type of small robot arm or

00:07:10.940 --> 00:07:11.940
whatever.

00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:15.660
It doesn't change what it is doing between the different things that run through the

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:17.179
assembly line.

00:07:17.179 --> 00:07:21.540
And methods for these classes, they span the assembly line.

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:28.260
So a class is not an object or a class is not really an area of the assembly line.

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.140
They are grouped based on what type of thing they are doing.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:34.420
So we have stat ggproto classes.

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:36.260
We have geom ggproto classes.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:44.779
And they might go in at different times in the rendering process and do their thing.

00:07:44.779 --> 00:07:50.619
So they might, like in time or in rendering time, they might come in at different points.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:56.420
So more formalized, we have this idea that we have generally in ggplot2.

00:07:56.420 --> 00:08:01.100
We take some data, we run it through some transformation, and there will be a plot.

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:05.820
And ggproto objects are really these kind of entities that sits at various points through

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:09.100
this pipeline of data to plot.

00:08:09.100 --> 00:08:14.320
And they have methods, and they modify the data, and then some other object takes over.

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:18.019
And that's modifying the data, maybe spits it back into the same object and so on and

00:08:18.019 --> 00:08:19.019
so forth.

00:08:19.019 --> 00:08:25.420
And then suddenly a plot appears, hopefully not disappears.

00:08:25.420 --> 00:08:32.900
So there are a few things in the ggproto classes that are shared between a lot of the different

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:33.900
implementations.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:36.380
And I'm just going to point out a few of them.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:41.059
I'm not going to get too much into exactly how you're going to write a new faceting function

00:08:41.059 --> 00:08:44.479
or how you're going to write a new position adjustment or whatever.

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:48.299
But just kind of highlighting a few of the things that you might potentially stumble

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:51.700
into when you're starting out with writing extensions.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:55.140
And one of the things that appears in almost all of the different extension points are

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:58.419
this setup param methods.

00:08:58.419 --> 00:09:02.979
And the reason why it's there is because, as I said, your objects are stateless.

00:09:02.979 --> 00:09:07.020
But if you want a state, and usually you want something, some kind of state based on the

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.039
data that you have in your plot, this is where you can get it.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:14.859
So this receives the data in the layer, and it receives it together with some of the parameters

00:09:14.859 --> 00:09:18.460
that you have defined when the user calls the plot.

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:24.140
And it can do whatever, and it can spit out a list of parameters that the ggplot2 rendering

00:09:24.140 --> 00:09:25.820
system then takes hold of.

00:09:25.820 --> 00:09:29.940
So it's not changing this data search, but it is returning a list of parameters that

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:34.380
will get passed in to the other different methods.

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:40.700
So it's kind of a pseudo stage that you are able to do.

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:45.940
And one of the places where it's getting spit in again is in this setup data method

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.820
that a lot of the different methods has as well.

00:09:48.820 --> 00:09:54.580
So it receives the data as well, and it receives these parameters that you have just calculated.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:57.979
So it's stateful, but it's just handled outside of the class.

00:09:57.979 --> 00:10:03.780
And what you can do in the setup data stage is that you can reparameterize data, which

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:07.260
is actually kind of a powerful concept.

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:12.140
There are a few geoms in ggplot2 which kind of does the same thing.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:16.219
For instance, you have geom segment, and then it's lesser well-known sibling called geom

00:10:16.219 --> 00:10:17.219
spoke.

00:10:17.219 --> 00:10:22.020
And the only difference between these two geoms is that geom segments takes the end

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:26.900
points of a segment and draws a line, while geom spoke takes a start point and an angle

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:29.400
and a length and draws a line.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:35.780
But behind it all, everything it does is really geom spoke is a subclass of geom segment,

00:10:36.299 --> 00:10:40.900
The only thing it does is it has a setup data which takes an angle, a start point, and a

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:43.260
length and calculates the new end point.

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:45.859
And then everything else just happens automatically.

00:10:45.859 --> 00:10:51.940
So if you have these kind of reparameterized stats or geoms, it's super simple to make

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:56.140
an extension, because the only thing you have to think about is to subclass it, provide

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:58.659
a new setup data method, and you're good to go.

00:10:58.659 --> 00:11:01.020
Everything else will just happen automatically.

00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:05.020
So this is a super important part, and you can really save yourself a lot of work by

00:11:05.020 --> 00:11:10.340
just thinking about whether some of the things that you want to achieve is already handled

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:12.179
by something else.

00:11:12.179 --> 00:11:16.940
You can also do stuff like make sure if there are some columns that you need to have, but

00:11:16.940 --> 00:11:22.659
the user doesn't necessarily want to define all the time, you can just inspect your data

00:11:22.659 --> 00:11:25.580
and see, well, does it miss the width column?

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:29.219
Well, OK, we'll set it to something sensible and so on.

00:11:29.219 --> 00:11:35.940
And just make sure that at this point, the data kind of makes sense for all of the remaining

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:39.500
steps of the object.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:44.260
Another quite important thing, especially when it comes to creating stats, which is

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:50.219
kind of one of the best places to start when creating extensions, is that the computation

00:11:50.219 --> 00:11:58.380
part, like the meat of a stat element in ggplot2 is this kind of tired succession of calls

00:11:58.539 --> 00:12:05.299
where you have a compute layer method, and by default, all it does is it's splitting

00:12:05.299 --> 00:12:09.739
up the layer data by the panels, and then it calls compute panel.

00:12:09.739 --> 00:12:14.299
And compute panel, by default, just splits up the panel data by the group aesthetic and

00:12:14.299 --> 00:12:16.099
calls compute group.

00:12:16.099 --> 00:12:22.460
So depending on where you want to sit in that kind of succession, you can define a compute

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:26.419
group method, which is kind of simple because you know you're only getting data for a single

00:12:26.419 --> 00:12:32.340
group at a time, and it may make it a lot easier to kind of figure out your computations.

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:38.020
But there's a lot of things that can be vectorized in R, and it might be stupidly inefficient

00:12:38.020 --> 00:12:40.460
to compute the same thing per group.

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:45.900
So you can just instead define a new compute panel method that does not call compute group

00:12:45.900 --> 00:12:48.479
but does everything in one step.

00:12:48.479 --> 00:12:55.260
So it's usually easier to start at compute group level, but you can quite easily make

00:12:55.260 --> 00:13:01.179
your geoms and stats more efficient by thinking about how can we efficiently do this in a

00:13:01.179 --> 00:13:03.619
vectorized manner.

00:13:03.619 --> 00:13:08.099
And these compute things, they simply just take some data along with additional parameters,

00:13:08.099 --> 00:13:09.859
and it spits out a new data frame.

00:13:09.859 --> 00:13:15.219
So this is a very simple part of this kind of assembly line where it just takes data,

00:13:15.219 --> 00:13:19.739
adds something to it or transforms it in some way and just spits out data again for the

00:13:19.739 --> 00:13:22.700
assembly line to take over again.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:28.179
If you want to do a geom instead of a stat, it's a bit different but kind of the same

00:13:28.179 --> 00:13:29.179
idea.

00:13:29.179 --> 00:13:32.020
We have a tight succession of calls again, and it's just draw layer, draw panel, draw

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:33.140
group.

00:13:33.140 --> 00:13:39.020
And again, sometimes you can vectorize things out, and you can really, really speed up your

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:40.020
drawing process.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:47.500
For instance, if you think about the geom point, if we had to draw each point once or

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:53.299
one at a time and create a function that takes the group and just draws one point one

00:13:53.299 --> 00:13:56.140
at a time, it will just be horribly inefficient.

00:13:56.140 --> 00:14:02.219
But thankfully, grid, that is the motor behind ggplot2, can just take a vector of point or

00:14:02.219 --> 00:14:03.219
coordinates.

00:14:03.219 --> 00:14:04.940
So we don't need to do this per group.

00:14:04.940 --> 00:14:09.859
We can do this per panel instead and really speed it up a thousand fold or something like

00:14:09.859 --> 00:14:10.859
that.

00:14:10.859 --> 00:14:14.820
So again, it's easier to start at the group level, but think about how you can speed things

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:17.739
up by vectorizing it properly.

00:14:17.739 --> 00:14:22.020
And this takes in data again, but this does not output data.

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:27.700
As Klaus talked about, there's this concept of grub in grids, which is graphical objects,

00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:32.619
and the purpose of the draw method is simply to return grubs that will then be rendered

00:14:32.619 --> 00:14:35.500
by grid in the end.

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:38.099
There are a lot of other methods that are being used.

00:14:38.099 --> 00:14:39.979
All of them are predefined.

00:14:39.979 --> 00:14:42.419
You will usually not come up with your own method.

00:14:42.419 --> 00:14:44.859
You will override the preexisting ones.

00:14:44.859 --> 00:14:48.260
And most of these have sensible defaults, and most of these you don't have to worry

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:50.099
about that much anyway.

00:14:50.099 --> 00:14:57.099
So in the end, I'll just try to put this into effect and make an extension.

00:14:57.099 --> 00:15:03.900
And we will do something as exciting as drawing a circle, because circles are just the best.

00:15:03.900 --> 00:15:09.020
And when you start out, you will just start to think about, well, how would I normally

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.320
draw a circle?

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:12.640
What is the defining features of a circle?

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:19.080
Well, you will have a midpoint, you will have a radius, and you will maybe remember from

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:24.840
geometry that a circle is defined by 0 to 2 times pi radians.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:30.159
That is kind of the different points along the periphery.

00:15:30.159 --> 00:15:35.400
And you can precompute some points along the periphery, and you can draw this with geom

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:38.000
polygon, and all works perfectly.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:42.159
So when you're in this situation, there's a lot of extensions that are in this situation.

00:15:42.159 --> 00:15:44.039
We want to draw some kind of shape.

00:15:44.039 --> 00:15:45.719
We want to draw some kind of line.

00:15:45.719 --> 00:15:48.520
Well, you don't have to think about how to draw shapes and lines.

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:51.520
We already have polygon functionality for this.

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:59.559
But we want to take some sort of input, and we want to calculate it inside the rendering

00:15:59.559 --> 00:16:01.080
code.

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:07.679
Then you're in the area of creating a stat, because it takes input data, and it recreates

00:16:08.359 --> 00:16:14.159
some new input or some new output data that can then be handled by geom polygon or whatever.

00:16:14.159 --> 00:16:19.799
So the first thing would probably be to put all of this into a function.

00:16:19.799 --> 00:16:25.679
So this is really just the same code that I had before the ggplot call.

00:16:25.679 --> 00:16:32.559
And what it simply does is take some input, and it calculates the angles and creates a

00:16:32.559 --> 00:16:35.840
data frame with the positions along the periphery.

00:16:35.840 --> 00:16:39.239
The reason why it's nice to do this is that it's very easy to reuse.

00:16:39.239 --> 00:16:44.039
It's much easier to debug, because I won't go into it, but ggproto methods are just horrible

00:16:44.039 --> 00:16:45.039
to debug.

00:16:45.039 --> 00:16:49.440
So you'd like to have the core functionality nicely defined in functions that you can put

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:53.359
browser in or debug them or whatever.

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:54.359
It's also way easier to document.

00:16:54.359 --> 00:16:56.760
So this is just, like, good habit.

00:16:56.760 --> 00:17:02.679
It's not necessary, but you'll thank me at one point.

00:17:02.679 --> 00:17:05.280
So now we have everything we need.

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:10.439
We are ready to create our extension, and this is actually the extension.

00:17:10.439 --> 00:17:16.959
It's pretty nice that you can have an extension that just fits up on one single slide.

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:19.520
This is a mouthful, and I'll go through it.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:24.560
One of the things that you need to think about is that you'll always subclass existing classes.

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:29.599
So you'll very, very seldom create a ggproto object from scratch.

00:17:29.599 --> 00:17:37.040
If you want to make a new stat, you will subclass the stat class or one of the other specified

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:40.599
stat classes, and you want to piggyback as much as possible.

00:17:40.599 --> 00:17:46.359
I said that faceting, for instance, is horribly complicated, but you can subclass facet wrap

00:17:46.359 --> 00:17:50.800
or facet grid, and you can actually kind of piggyback on all the complicated stuff and

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:57.640
do some pretty amazing things without thinking too much about the horrible stuff.

00:17:57.640 --> 00:18:02.800
So the first thing is the class construction, and we have this ggproto function.

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:03.800
We name it.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:09.239
We say inherit it from stat, and then we save it to a stat circ.

00:18:09.239 --> 00:18:11.640
And then we simply just define our different methods.

00:18:11.640 --> 00:18:13.839
We have the setup data that we talked about.

00:18:13.839 --> 00:18:18.439
The only thing that's happening here is that we want to ensure that a group aesthetic exists

00:18:18.439 --> 00:18:26.079
and that it is different for each row because each row defines a circle.

00:18:26.079 --> 00:18:30.479
So we simply just make sure that that happens, and then we have the compute group, as we

00:18:30.479 --> 00:18:36.119
talked about, and this simply just calls our function, and that's more or less it.

00:18:36.119 --> 00:18:39.160
And in the end, we also have some other things that we can set.

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:45.239
We can say, well, this statistics requires a certain number of aesthetics.

00:18:45.239 --> 00:18:50.319
Here we say, well, you need to specify x zero, you need to specify y zero, you need to specify

00:18:50.319 --> 00:18:51.319
an r.

00:18:51.319 --> 00:18:55.359
And then when we initialize this stat transform, we'll simply just say, meh, I don't want to

00:18:55.359 --> 00:18:58.199
do that.

00:18:58.199 --> 00:19:01.000
So this is really it.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.439
The reason why you seldom see this type of objects is, of course, that they are packaged

00:19:05.439 --> 00:19:11.560
into nice little containers, stat underscore circ for the circle for this, or gm underscore

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:12.560
circle.

00:19:12.560 --> 00:19:14.079
I'm not going into detail.

00:19:14.079 --> 00:19:19.560
These are really, really simple to create, but it's just a lot of scaffolding code, and

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:24.000
you can just simply see how it's being done in ggplot2, and it's really simple.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
It's just a lot of code.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.839
So I won't bore you with that.

00:19:26.839 --> 00:19:29.619
So now we have our circle.

00:19:29.619 --> 00:19:30.619
And does it work?

00:19:30.619 --> 00:19:31.660
Yes, it does.

00:19:31.660 --> 00:19:37.400
So as you can see, we can now simply use our gm circle inside a ggplot2 call, and it behaves

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:39.199
as we expect it to.

00:19:39.199 --> 00:19:43.599
And the nice thing about this is that this now functions with all the different things

00:19:43.599 --> 00:19:45.040
that you expect in ggplot2.

00:19:45.040 --> 00:19:49.280
So you can do faceting, you can do whatever and all that.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.079
So as I said, this is a very, very brief overview.

00:19:53.079 --> 00:19:57.479
One of the things that I want to emphasize is that the ggplot2 book, which has been on

00:19:57.479 --> 00:20:01.359
sale for a long time, we're working on a third edition.

00:20:01.359 --> 00:20:08.640
It's going to be free, as most of our other books, so you can already see it here, ggplot2-book.org.

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:13.680
And I'm working on actual chapters talking a bit about extensions, going into more details

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:15.920
about how you will approach this.

00:20:15.920 --> 00:20:19.760
And thankfully, we also have a huge community of people that are building extensions.

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:29.479
A lot of these are based on or are referenced in this ggplot2-web page.

00:20:29.479 --> 00:20:31.739
And the best way to learn is simply by example.

00:20:31.739 --> 00:20:36.359
So there is a lot of examples of creating both super easy extensions and more hairy

00:20:36.359 --> 00:20:37.880
and gnarly ones.

